Anonymous Thu 05 Sep 2024 21:51:43 No.68898509 Report
Quoted By: >>68898603 >>68898622 >>68898977 >>68899012 >>68899221
I will say, as an artist myself who spends probably every day trying to get better at his craft, AI is discouraging. Last year I laughed at the goofy cognitohazards it produced. Now it's nearly passable, so I can't imagine where it will be in a year. It does make one stop and go 'what's the point of trying anymore?' increasingly with each passing day. If you can snap your fingers and just have several finished variants of a piece to pick from, there's no reason to struggle to learn how to make anything yourself.

You can argue about artists being upset about getting money for gooner content, and the need for money is true. We all have to eat don't we? But, believe this or not, it's robbing people like me of the joy of creation. Of the sense of purpose. When you spend hours painstakingly crafting and pushing yourself to the limits of your skill to try to surpass your previous stuff it...feels fulfilling. It feels meaningful. And knowing what you produce will make someone happy gives me a little touch of pride, something I rarely get to feel. But with AI just displacing artists so rapidly it's just...anything I bust my ass and make will be littered with moments of "Why bother, AI can run circles around me in seconds?" thought intrusions.

Eventually, it'll win, and drawing won't be fulfilling anymore. And AI won't fill that void for me, because its just instant. There's no training on your end, no skills required. Nothing learned or gained, just more consumption.

Just to be clear, I was never one of those people who took joy when other peoples jobs were automated. I sympathized, and I'm sure there are a lot of other artists out there who were the same. Not all artists and writers were those liberal 'I'm better than you' dickheads who delighted in blue-collar workers losing jobs until the AI beast slouched toward their fields.
